*** 1.1.56 Rabbinic Judaism Response

Reality consists of HaShem as infinite Creator and all creation existing according to divine will revealed through Torah (Written and Oral) requiring human sanctification through mitzvot (commandments), study, and communal life according to halakhah (Jewish law) as interpreted through rabbinic hermeneutics, Talmudic dialectics, and responsa literature. Rabbinic Judaism, emerging from Second Temple destruction (70 CE) and consolidating at Yavneh under Yochanan ben Zakkai, transformed biblical religion into portable, text-centered, community-based Judaism enabling survival without Temple, priesthood, or sovereignty through revolutionary innovations: transferring sanctity from Jerusalem Temple to home, synagogue, and study house; replacing sacrificial cult with prayer, study, and mitzvot; vesting religious authority in Torah scholars rather than hereditary priests; and developing interpretive frameworks enabling Torah application to changing circumstances while maintaining eternal divine revelation's authority. Dual Torah concept—Written Torah (Tanakh) complemented by Oral Torah (Mishnah, Talmud, later rabbinic literature) transmitted from Sinai through rabbinic chain of tradition—established framework wherein revelation includes interpretive principles enabling ongoing legal development. This rabbinic revolution created Judaism's dominant form for two millennia, establishing frameworks continuing to shape contemporary Jewish life across denominations despite modern challenges to rabbinic authority, traditional cosmology, and halakhic absolutism.

Historical development proceeded through distinct periods. Tannaitic era (1st-2nd centuries) witnessed Mishnah's compilation (c. 200 CE) by Judah HaNasi organizing oral traditions into six orders covering agriculture, festivals, family law, civil-criminal law, sacrifices, and purity. Palestinian and Babylonian Amoraim (3rd-5th centuries) produced Talmuds—Palestinian Talmud (c. 400) and more authoritative Babylonian Talmud (c. 500)—preserving dialectical analysis, legal rulings, and aggadic (narrative-theological) material. Geonic period (6th-11th centuries) centered in Babylonian academies (Sura, Pumbedita) answering questions and establishing Babylonian Talmud's authority through responsa literature. Rishonim period (11th-15th centuries) produced towering scholars: Rashi (1040-1105) whose Talmud commentary remains indispensable; Maimonides (1138-1204) synthesizing Jewish law philosophically in Mishneh Torah and Guide for the Perplexed; Tosafists developing dialectical analysis; and Spanish-Provençal scholars engaging Islamic and Christian philosophy. Acharonim period (16th century onward) witnessed Shulchan Aruch's codification by Joseph Caro (1563) becoming standard halakhic reference, Hasidic movement emerging (18th century) emphasizing devotion and mysticism over Talmudic scholarship alone, and Mitnagdic response defending traditional learning. Modernity brought unprecedented challenges: Enlightenment questioning revelation, emancipation enabling secular Jewish identity, Reform movement rejecting halakhic authority, and Holocaust devastating European rabbinic centers. Contemporary Judaism spans denominations from Haredi maintaining traditional authority to Reform emphasizing autonomy, with Conservative, Modern Orthodox, and Reconstructionist movements negotiating tradition and modernity variously.

Core principles include: First, monotheism—HaShem as one, indivisible, incorporeal Creator. Second, revelation—Torah from heaven (Torah min haShamayim) including Written and Oral Torah. Third, covenant—Israel's eternal election and responsibility. Fourth, halakhah—comprehensive legal system governing ritual, ethical, civil, and criminal domains. Fifth, study as worship—Torah study as supreme religious act encountering divine will. Sixth, community—minyan (quorum) required for full worship, emphasizing corporate rather than merely individual religious life. Seventh, ethical monotheism—ritual and ethics integrated through comprehensive mitzvot system. Eighth, messianic hope—awaiting Davidic Messiah, Temple restoration, and redemption. Ninth, resurrection of dead—eschatological belief in future bodily resurrection. Tenth, this-worldly emphasis—sanctifying material existence rather than escaping to spiritual realm.

