Core Hasidic principles include: First, devekut—constant God-consciousness through mystical awareness. Second, avodah b'gashmiyut—serving God through material activities elevated by intention. Third, tzaddik doctrine—rebbe as spiritual master, intercessor, and living Torah whose soul level enables channeling divine influence. Fourth, joy (simchah) as religious obligation—melancholy impedes divine service. Fifth, niggunim (wordless melodies) expressing soul's yearning. Sixth, hitlahavut (enthusiasm) in prayer and mitzvot. Seventh, bittul (self-nullification) transcending ego. Eighth, divine immanence—God's presence filling creation requiring no meditation bridging distance. Ninth, birur nitzutzot—elevating divine sparks through proper use of materiality. Tenth, storytelling—rebbe tales transmitting inspiration and teaching. Eleventh, customs (minhagim) distinguishing dynasties in dress, liturgy, stringencies. Twelfth, insularity—protecting spirituality through cultural separation.

