Human consciousness manifests the rational soul's (anima rationalis) spiritual nature through its capacity for intellectual knowledge (intellectus) and free choice (liberum arbitrium), demonstrating immateriality through operations that transcend the limitations of material causality and physical determination. The rational soul constitutes the substantial form (forma substantialis) of the human body according to Thomistic hylomorphism, establishing human beings as substantial unities (unum simpliciter) rather than accidental composites of separate substances, with consciousness emerging from this fundamental soul-body unity. The intellect's capacity for abstracting universal concepts (universalia) from particular sense data, grasping mathematical truths, and engaging in reflexive self-knowledge (reditio completa in seipsum) demonstrates its immaterial nature, since material faculties can only receive individual forms through physical modification and cannot achieve complete self-reflection. Personal identity (identitas personalis) depends essentially on the continuity of the individual rational soul, which persists through all bodily changes and survives corporeal death, maintaining consciousness in the separated state (status animae separatae) while naturally inclining toward reunion with its proper body in the resurrection. Self-consciousness (conscientia sui) involves the soul's spiritual reflexivity upon its own cognitive and volitional acts, enabling the human person to achieve transcendence over immediate material conditions through intellectual abstraction and moral self-determination. The will's freedom (libertas) manifests through the capacity to choose between genuine alternatives based on intellectual apprehension of the good (appetitus rationalis), distinguishing human action from animal behavior governed by sensory appetite (appetitus sensitivus) and material conditioning. Consciousness encompasses multiple levels: vegetative (shared with plants), sensitive (shared with animals), and intellectual (unique to rational beings), with the latter enabling abstract conceptual thought, moral reasoning, and supernatural relationship with God through grace. The unity of consciousness reflects the soul's simplicity as the single substantial principle organizing all vital functions, from basic metabolism through sensory perception to intellectual understanding, preventing the reduction of mental phenomena to mere epiphenomena of neural activity. Memory (memoria) operates through both material processes in the sensory imagination (phantasia) and spiritual processes in the intellectual memory, with the latter preserving intelligible species and enabling personal continuity, moral responsibility, and progressive intellectual development. Emotions (passiones animae) involve integrated responses engaging both bodily changes and spiritual movements, representing human nature as embodied spirit (spiritus incarnatus) rather than pure intelligence accidentally united to matter. The moral dimension of consciousness appears in conscience (conscientia), where practical reason applies universal moral principles to particular circumstances under the natural law inscribed in human nature and illuminated by divine law. Free will operates through the interplay of intellect presenting the good and will choosing among alternatives, with authentic freedom consisting in the capacity to choose genuine goods rather than mere absence of constraint or determination. Dreams, mystical experiences, and altered states of consciousness may indicate the soul's spiritual transcendence over material limitations, though requiring careful discernment according to orthodox theological criteria to distinguish authentic spiritual phenomena from natural psychological processes. Mental illness affects consciousness through disruptions in the soul-body relationship without destroying the soul's essential spiritual nature or the person's fundamental dignity, requiring both medical treatment addressing material causes and spiritual care addressing the whole human person. The ultimate destiny of human consciousness is the beatific vision (visio beatifica), where the glorified soul united to its resurrected body will know God immediately through the divine essence itself, surpassing all natural cognitive capacities through the light of glory (lumen gloriae).

