Beauty constitutes one of the transcendental properties of being (transcendentalia entis) alongside truth and goodness, reflecting God's own divine beauty as the ultimate source, exemplar, and final cause of all created beauty through analogical participation in divine perfection. Objective beauty possesses ontological reality grounded in the metaphysical principles of proportion (proportio), integrity (integritas), and clarity (claritas) that Thomas Aquinas identified as beauty's essential characteristics, establishing aesthetic judgment as rational apprehension rather than mere subjective preference or cultural conditioning. The beautiful serves as a via pulchritudinis (way of beauty) toward divine knowledge through its capacity to evoke intellectual wonder, contemplative attraction, and desire for the infinite good that finite beauty simultaneously reveals and conceals through analogical participation in uncreated beauty. Sacred art (ars sacra) fulfills essential liturgical, catechetical, and evangelistic functions by rendering visible the invisible mysteries of faith through material media elevated by divine grace, requiring both technical excellence (ars) and spiritual authenticity from artists who participate in the Church's prophetic mission. The Incarnation establishes the definitive theological foundation for Christian aesthetics, as the Word's assumption of human nature validates matter's intrinsic capacity to mediate spiritual reality without pantheistic confusion, providing the ontological basis for sacramental principle and sacred artistic representation. Beauty's essential relationship to truth and goodness (pulchrum, verum, bonum) means authentic artistic expression must respect both moral order and ontological reality, rejecting aestheticism that divorces beauty from truth and didactic reductionism that subordinates artistic value to utilitarian messaging. The artist participates analogically in divine creative activity (participatio in divina creativitate) through the gifts of imagination, technical skill, and spiritual insight, bearing moral responsibility to employ these talents for integral human development and divine glorification rather than mere self-expression, commercial exploitation, or ideological manipulation. Religious art should inspire authentic devotion, instruct the faithful in sacred doctrine, and beautify liturgical spaces through forms that elevate mind and heart toward divine contemplation, following traditional iconographic principles while permitting legitimate organic development guided by ecclesiastical authority. The hierarchy of beauty corresponds analogically to the hierarchy of being, with spiritual beauty (pulchrum spirituale) transcending material beauty, moral beauty exceeding merely aesthetic beauty, and divine beauty infinitely surpassing all created forms while remaining their ultimate source, measure, and final end. Popular culture and entertainment possess significant moral implications through their formative influence on human consciousness and behavior, requiring prudential discernment regarding their conformity to Christian anthropology and their effects on virtue, vice, and spiritual development. The cultivation of aesthetic judgment involves both natural education in classical principles of beauty discovered through philosophical analysis and supernatural formation through active participation in the Church's liturgical life, artistic traditions, and contemplative practice. Ugliness, artistic degradation, and aesthetic disorder often manifest spiritual corruption and the distortion of human nature through sin's effects, though authentic artistic treatment of tragic themes may serve truth and moral instruction when ultimately ordered toward transcendence and redemption. The restoration of beauty in contemporary art and culture represents a crucial dimension of the New Evangelization, as beauty's inherent attractive power draws human hearts toward the truth and goodness